article.description: Nicole Powell hit four 3-pointers and had 20 points and nine rebounds to lead the Sacramento Monarchs past the Houston Comets 80-65 on Saturday night.
article.shortLinkText: Powell, Lawson 3-pointers propel Comets to win
article.headline: Monarchs take control in third quarter for another home win
article.linkText: Powell, Lawson 3-pointers propel Monarchs to win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO , Calif. -- Fighting for a postseason bid in the tight Western Conference, every game feels like the playoffs for the Sacramento Monarchs.

Thanks to the play of Nicole Powell, the Monarchs are one step closer to their goal. She hit four 3-pointers and had 20 points and nine rebounds to lead fourth-place Sacramento past the Houston Comets 80-65 on Saturday night.

The victory snapped a two-game losing streak and kept the Monarchs (16-13) in control of the conference's final playoff berth, and just one game behind Los Angeles.

"Look at the standings, how tight everything is, there is lot of desperation going on right now with every team," said Powell, who rebounded from a poor shooting game Thursday in a loss to Los Angeles. "We only have five games left so everyone is very important."

Sacramento outscored Houston 30-14 in the third to take control, highlighted by 13 unanswered points early in the quarter that gave them a 53-39 lead.

Powell made two straight 3-pointers and Kara Lawson followed with another to key the spurt that helped Sacramento take a comfortable 70-51 lead into the final quarter.

"Sacramento came out with a sense of urgency," Houston coach Karleen Thompson said. "We didn't execute and their defense made it uncomfortable for us. They were the aggressors tonight."

Lawson also had four 3-pointers and finished with 14 points for the Monarchs, who have won nine of 10 games at home. Crystal Kelly had 12 points, Scholanda Robinson added 11 and Adrian Williams-Strong had eight points and eight rebounds.

The Monarchs will have nearly a week off, then play three of the their final five games on the road, starting Friday at Phoenix.

"I think it will be good for us to get in some more practice time," said Lawson, a key reserve on the gold medal-winning U.S. Olympic team. "I'm just glad to be in one place for a bit in the same time zone."

It was a difficult evening for another U.S. Olympic star, Tina Thompson. The Houston forward went to the bench early in the first quarter with two fouls and played sparingly in the third quarter following a couple of turnovers. She finished with 12 points and seven rebounds.

Shannon Johnson had 12 points and five assists, but committed six of Houston 's 21 turnovers.

It was the second straight loss for Houston (14-14), which had won five straight before the Olympic break. The loss dropped the Comets into sixth place, a half-game behind Minnesota.

"That's how tight it is in the West, one night you win and you're in the playoffs and the next one you lose and you're not," coach Thompson said.

Houston, which is 3-12 on the road this season, plays four of its six remaining games at home, where it has won eight straight. The Comets' final game is Sept. 12 against Sacramento .

The Comets played without key reserves Sancho Lyttle and Hamchetou Maiga-Ba, who are injured. Rebekkah Brunson, who had knee surgery on Aug. 6, missed her second straight game for Sacramento.
